==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈkleɪm/}}
* {{rhymes|eɪm}}

===Etymology 1===
* First attested in the early 14th century.
* {{sense|to applaud}} First attested in the 1630's.
* From {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|acclamo|acclāmō|raise a cry at; applaud|lang=la}}, formed from {{term|ad-|lang=la}} + {{term|clamo|clāmō|cry out, shout|lang=la}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[shout]]; to [[call out]].
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To shout approval; to express great [[approval]].
# {{context|transitive|rare|lang=en}} To [[salute]] or [[praise]] with great approval; to [[compliment]]; to [[applaud]]; to [[welcome]] enthusiastically.
#* A glad '''acclaiming''' train. - Thomson
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[claim]].
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[declare]] by [[acclamations]].
#* While the shouting crowd / '''Acclaims''' thee king of traitors. - Smollett
# {{context|Canada|politics|lang=en}} To elect to an office by having no opposition.

